<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>might be simpler if...</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?Tempra[CC]">Tempra[CC]</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 2:36 p.m. 9/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> might be simpler if...<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=378" TARGET=_self>Addendum: Individual vs Group</A> (TheBlack[BCK])
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>Your method is well thought out but it is kind of complicated.. It would be simple to stay with the idea of +/-(whatever lvl people decide on) above the highest person and below the lowest person... like i said earlier there are problems of level 50's grouping with level 1's just so they can attack anyone, but i suggest thata group limit of 10-15 levels should be sufficient to satisfy everyone.

<P>Tempra[CC]
<P>I've mentioned this idea in older postings but I'll reiterate it
<BR>&gt; here as it solves a potential problem with my system...
<P>&gt; If an individual attacks a member of a group, and that
<BR>&gt; individual does *not* fall within the GAR range of the group
<BR>&gt; (they are below the range), then the player they attacked is
<BR>&gt; automatically booted out of the group and PvP is initiated
<BR>&gt; between the two players.
<P>&gt; This addresses the following scenario. Group A consists of lvl
<BR>&gt; 6, 25, 26, 27, and 30. The GAR of A is 24 to 36. While the 6th
<BR>&gt; is in this group he is basically shielded from attack by other
<BR>&gt; groups who are either unable or unwilling to attack A to get to
<BR>&gt; him.
<BR>&gt; Now, if an individiual, say level 9, attacked the level 6, then
<BR>&gt; the level 6 player is ejected from the group and PvP begins. No
<BR>&gt; one in group A can interfere as the level 9 is both below group
<BR>&gt; A's GAR and the level 9 is more than 4 levels below every other
<BR>&gt; member of group A.
<P>&gt; This would also implicitly be the case however if a group B,
<BR>&gt; levels 5, 6, 7, and 9, were to come along and attack group A. In
<BR>&gt; this
<BR>&gt; situation the group engages only the player that falls within
<BR>&gt; it's GAR, and the player is ejected and combat begins. The
<BR>&gt; determining factor in whether group B is attacking group A or
<BR>&gt; just the individual is if the player in group A that is being
<BR>&gt; attacked is below 1/2 the level of the highest member of group
<BR>&gt; A, then it's an individual attack. Otherwise it's a group
<BR>&gt; attack.
<BR>&gt; So any member below level 15 that is in group A (30 / 2), could
<BR>&gt; be individually attacked by lower level players. If the 6th
<BR>&gt; level player were instead level 15, and group B attacked the 15,
<BR>&gt; then it would be an attack on group A and all the members of
<BR>&gt; group A could retaliate.
<P>&gt; Alerternative Individual Attack Rule: Instead of taking the max
<BR>&gt; char level / 2, take the lower limit of the GAR and any
<BR>&gt; character attacked that is not within the group's GAR is treated
<BR>&gt; as an individual attack instead of a group attack. This would
<BR>&gt; mean that stronger groups could NOT shelter lower level players.
<BR>&gt; In the lvl/2 method higher level groups can shelter some levels
<BR>&gt; of players. Using the GAR range is probably a better approach,
<BR>&gt; but the algorithm may need to be adjusted outwards as level
<BR>&gt; increases so that groups with a 40 or a 50 have broader GAR
<BR>&gt; ranges than those with a 20 or 30 ( level / 10 * 1.5 might
<BR>&gt; work).
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
